Q40. What is a tuple? How is it different from list?
A tuple is an ordered sequence of elements of different data types, such as integer, float, string, list or even a tuple.
Elements of a tuple are enclosed in parenthesis (round brackets) and are separated by commas
List and Tuple in Python are the classes of Python Data Structures. The list is dynamic, whereas the tuple has static characteristics. 
This means that lists can be modified whereas tuples cannot be modified, the tuple is faster than the list because of static in nature.

Q41. How can you create a tuple in Python?
A tuple is created by placing all the items (elements) inside parentheses () , separated by commas.
my_tuple = (1, "Hello", 3.4)

